<div id="review_4023256175" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4023256175" />
    <a title="Ola Madhour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/128623868-ola-madhour"><img alt="Ola Madhour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619119826p2/128623868.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4023256175?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ola Madhour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ola Madhour" href="/user/show/128623868-ola-madhour">Ola Madhour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307278365" href="/book/show/9472737-the-sunset-limited">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/128623868-ola-madhour?shelf=plays">plays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4023256175" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16588783321914448198">I am not a fan of Cormac McCarthy—I know he’s great, intellectually I know, but he can’t write women and sometimes I just want punctuation, please? And God knows I have tried with <i>Blood Meridian</i>! It’s a great American novel and yet I can’t get through it, just like I can’t get through Pynchon’s <i>Gravity’s Rainbow</i> or DeLillo’s <i>Underworld</i>. As for <i>The Road</i> and <i>No Country for Old Men</i>… well, I thought the movies were good. <br/><br/><i>The Sunset Limited</i>, however, is something else entirely. A friend of mine recom</span>
  <span id="freeText16588783321914448198" style="display:none">I am not a fan of Cormac McCarthy—I know he’s great, intellectually I know, but he can’t write women and sometimes I just want punctuation, please? And God knows I have tried with <i>Blood Meridian</i>! It’s a great American novel and yet I can’t get through it, just like I can’t get through Pynchon’s <i>Gravity’s Rainbow</i> or DeLillo’s <i>Underworld</i>. As for <i>The Road</i> and <i>No Country for Old Men</i>… well, I thought the movies were good. <br /><br /><i>The Sunset Limited</i>, however, is something else entirely. A friend of mine recommended it even though she knows that McCarthy and I don't get along. She said, “read it, it’s a play, you’ll like it.” She was right, I loved it. And yes it’s a play, but not really. It’s more of a conversation, some sort of a philosophical debate between a white man named White and a black man named Black. White is an educated professor who is in great mental distress and Black, an optimistic Christian man, desperately attempts to convince him that life is worth living. The play opposes a nihilistic view of the world with a faith-driven one. <br /><br />This is not new of course—an atheist and a believer arguing—but here it’s not too dramatic and it’s not cliché. It’s Socratic at times and quite intellectual, but then it becomes Nietzschean and raw when it pulls at your guts and makes you confront your demons. You really <i>feel</i> the pain, the frustration, the despair, the angst that the characters go through. At least it was the case for me. <br /><br />I am thrilled to have read anything by McCarthy. One day I might give <i>Blood Meridian</i> another try. Who knows.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16588783321914448198" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


