<div id="review_428864726" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/428864726" />
    <a title="Darwin8u" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2294090-darwin8u"><img alt="Darwin8u" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1547440402p2/2294090.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/428864726?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Darwin8u" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Darwin8u" href="/user/show/2294090-darwin8u">Darwin8u</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780330518192" href="/book/show/9759934-sunset-limited">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2294090-darwin8u?shelf=2013">2013</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer428864726" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5046878742080312936">Black and White discussing God, Suffering, Death &amp; the Sunset Limited. This novel/play reminds me of Beckett&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17716.Waiting_for_Godot' title='Waiting for Godot by Samuel Beckett' rel='nofollow noopener'>Waiting for Godot</a>, Hesse&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/52036.Siddhartha' title='Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse' rel='nofollow noopener'>Siddhartha</a> and Wiesel&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11161.The_Trial_of_God__as_it_was_held_on_February_25__1649__in_Shamgorod_' title='The Trial of God (as it was held on February 25, 1649, in Shamgorod) by Elie Wiesel' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Trial of God</a>. <br/><br/>&apos;Sunset Limited&apos; has definite moments of intense brilliance, emotional resonance and spiritual affirmation followed by pages of lonely darkness and cold, existential dispair. While it WAS engaging (especially the dialogue), I just didn&apos;t think it was novel or transformative. Like WfG, Siddhartha and ToG, the Sunset Lim</span>
  <span id="freeText5046878742080312936" style="display:none">Black and White discussing God, Suffering, Death &amp; the Sunset Limited. This novel/play reminds me of Beckett's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17716.Waiting_for_Godot" title="Waiting for Godot by Samuel Beckett" rel="nofollow noopener">Waiting for Godot</a>, Hesse's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/52036.Siddhartha" title="Siddhartha by Hermann Hesse" rel="nofollow noopener">Siddhartha</a> and Wiesel's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/11161.The_Trial_of_God__as_it_was_held_on_February_25__1649__in_Shamgorod_" title="The Trial of God (as it was held on February 25, 1649, in Shamgorod) by Elie Wiesel" rel="nofollow noopener">The Trial of God</a>. <br /><br />'Sunset Limited' has definite moments of intense brilliance, emotional resonance and spiritual affirmation followed by pages of lonely darkness and cold, existential dispair. While it WAS engaging (especially the dialogue), I just didn't think it was novel or transformative. Like WfG, Siddhartha and ToG, the Sunset Limited just seems a tad too didactic. In the end, it was a minor McCarthy playing with ideas of the twilight.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5046878742080312936" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


