<div id="review_3270959509" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3270959509" />
    <a title="Leo Robertson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7619789-leo-robertson"><img alt="Leo Robertson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571602096p2/7619789.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3270959509?book_show_action=true">Apr 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leo Robertson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leo Robertson" href="/user/show/7619789-leo-robertson">Leo Robertson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3270959509" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7742075015464420937">Fascinating!<br/><br/>I enjoy the restrictions of the single-room drama--this is the only time I&apos;ve seen a two-person play/film etc stretched to a full 90 mins compellingly. Everyone else should bail early (like The Lighthouse recently—yeugh! All those lovely images and that great acting, only not to have a point? Let me off island already!! Or that film Blue Jay--longest 50 mins of my life. The film is 80 mins long but I&apos;m not stupid haha.)<br/><br/>Especially since it doesn&apos;t really seem to have an unfolding plot</span>
  <span id="freeText7742075015464420937" style="display:none">Fascinating!<br /><br />I enjoy the restrictions of the single-room drama--this is the only time I've seen a two-person play/film etc stretched to a full 90 mins compellingly. Everyone else should bail early (like The Lighthouse recently—yeugh! All those lovely images and that great acting, only not to have a point? Let me off island already!! Or that film Blue Jay--longest 50 mins of my life. The film is 80 mins long but I'm not stupid haha.)<br /><br />Especially since it doesn't really seem to have an unfolding plot. There are backstories here and there but it's basically just an evolving conversation of ideas. But it succeeds because those ideas are of the highest order--life and death, optimism and pessimism, faith and atheism. McCarthy once said that literature is only serious if it considers life and death--but, just like any writer, he has only created a yardstick by which he can measure the value of his own work. It's a good one as it obviously ensures the quality of his own writing, but I don't think writing without this depth is also without value. This coming from someone who enjoys binge-watching mumblecore films, which are about middle class white people who can't get their lives together, hahaha... "Like she texted me and like like like"<br /><br />I watched the film, which has the acting firepower required to keep the viewer glued to two people in dialogue for the length it takes to get through--but once again I enjoy reading "plays" more than seeing them. People put such care into condensed words only for actors to fling them at each other faster than I can comprehend, haha! </span>
  <a data-text-id="7742075015464420937" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


