    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_849132736" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/849132736" />
    <a title="Reid" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6903379-reid"><img alt="Reid" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612670226p2/6903379.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/849132736?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Reid" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Reid" href="/user/show/6903379-reid">Reid</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307278365" href="/book/show/9472737-the-sunset-limited">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Reid by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/2266055-daniel-villines">Daniel Villines</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6903379-reid?shelf=2014">2014</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6903379-reid?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6903379-reid?shelf=4-stars">4-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6903379-reid?shelf=literature-classics">literature-classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6903379-reid?shelf=lol">lol</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6903379-reid?shelf=review">review</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6903379-reid?shelf=drama">drama</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer849132736" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6937563541973677373">This is a great dialogue. It really does resonate, including swipes at western civilization, racism, classism, free will, and intellectual elitism, not just suicide, religious belief, and free thinking. If you ask me, Mr Black kicks Mr White&apos;s ass all the way back to the Sunset Limited, ie, Mr White lost this game of the Dozens big time, despite the fact White thinks he won and Black thinks he himself lost. Not that I can&apos;t relate to the major depressive Mr White - I was Mr White last year, but </span>
  <span id="freeText6937563541973677373" style="display:none">This is a great dialogue. It really does resonate, including swipes at western civilization, racism, classism, free will, and intellectual elitism, not just suicide, religious belief, and free thinking. If you ask me, Mr Black kicks Mr White's ass all the way back to the Sunset Limited, ie, Mr White lost this game of the Dozens big time, despite the fact White thinks he won and Black thinks he himself lost. Not that I can't relate to the major depressive Mr White - I was Mr White last year, but if you're lucky your alter ego, Mr Black, steps in and saves you from being mesmerized by an on coming train. I haven't read other McCarthy books, but I assume with all the violence that he's saying western civ. has reached a point of near-no return. <br /><br />Mr Black has some really great lines, and by lines I mean counter arguments to Mr White's nihilistic pessimistic suicidal point of view. The choice is pretty much black and white, yet the back and forth argument, too, is mesmerizing and worthy of your attention. It leaves me thinking (and maybe this is partially McCarthy's intent) that we need to choose sides, or at least not be mesmerized by any tennis match - do you support yourself and your brother, or do you suffer and die together in front of each others' eyes? Mr White's final straw: "Western Civilization finally went up in smoke in the chimneys at Dachau... I see it now." Mr White complains of the death of western civ, and Mr Black points out, essentially, that the culture of rational scientific pursuit has splintered everything exponentially, burying us into an ever-growing heap of meaningless pieces. It's kind of fascinating when the two sides essentially agree or run parallel, like Black's leap of faith and White's leap toward the train.<br /><br />The book, too, is accurate and pointed, psychologically, and it's comical to boot. And I do see, feel, and suffer both sides of the argument, but it's interesting to contemplate the consequences of each side. Definitely recommended.<br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="6937563541973677373" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


