    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_136045587" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/136045587" />
    <a title="Daniel Villines" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2266055-daniel-villines"><img alt="Daniel Villines" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1536179787p2/2266055.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/136045587?book_show_action=true">Dec 21, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel Villines" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel Villines" href="/user/show/2266055-daniel-villines">Daniel Villines</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer136045587" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7289668953690996793">Amazingly simple, yet amazing none-the-less; in my mind, McCarthy is at par with Greene in his ability to make the human condition into something that can be visualized and contemplated. <br/><br/>Within <i>The Sunset Limited</i> two extreme points of view are pitted against each other for a debate of words. In doing so, evidence is presented to a jury comprised of the solitary reader. While McCarthy allows free will to decide the ending, the deliberation of the evidence occupies the reader&apos;s mind during the sil</span>
  <span id="freeText7289668953690996793" style="display:none">Amazingly simple, yet amazing none-the-less; in my mind, McCarthy is at par with Greene in his ability to make the human condition into something that can be visualized and contemplated. <br /><br />Within <i>The Sunset Limited</i> two extreme points of view are pitted against each other for a debate of words. In doing so, evidence is presented to a jury comprised of the solitary reader. While McCarthy allows free will to decide the ending, the deliberation of the evidence occupies the reader's mind during the silence that exists in the room after the back cover is closed. <br /><br />My conclusions may not be your conclusions. The fact that McCarthy allows for this freedom of thought by the reader shows his acute understanding of how powerful words can be once placed in the minds of his audience and his ability to tap into this source of power makes for one amazing reading experience.<br /><br />As for style, his prose written in "dramatic format" probably reach the pinnacle of his apparent quest to communicate the most meaningful elements of life with the fewest amounts of words. Place <i>The Road</i> on a medium heat as if it were a cup of sugar and reduce its volume down to a tablespoon of caramel and you have <i>The Sunset Limited</i>.<br /><br />I would recommend this book to anyone who wished to consider the human condition from both a spiritual and a realist point of view. There are also psychoanalytical elements to this book that are worth exploring given the protagonist's personal outlooks on life and humanity, and the effects that these outlooks have on his behavior.<br /> <br />I'll be thinking about this book for some time to come.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7289668953690996793" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


